03972nam a22005775i 9780774864145DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20202020xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807748641457 a10.59962/97807748641452doi  a(DE-B1597)661425  a(OCoLC)1163891272  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aHQ1220.C2bG46 2020 7aSOC0280002bisacsh04a791.6/609712231 aGentile, Patrizia, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aQueen of the Maple Leaf :bBeauty Contests and Settler Femininity /cPatrizia Gentile. 1aVancouver ;aToronto : bUniversity of British Columbia Press, c[2020] 4cÂ©2020  a1 online resource (292 p.) :b12 b&w photos  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aSexuality Studies00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tAbbreviations -- tIntroduction -- tBeauty Queens and (White) Settler Nationalism -- tMiss Canada and Gendering Whiteness -- tLabour of Beauty -- tContesting Indigenous, Immigrant, and Black Bodies -- tMiss Canada, Commercialization, and Settler Anxiety -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAs modern versions of the settler nation took root in twentieth-century Canada, beauty emerged as a business. But beauty pageants were more than just frivolous spectacles. Queen of the Maple Leaf deftly uncovers how colonial power operated within the pageant circuit. Patrizia Gentile examines the interplay between local or community-based pageants and provincial or national ones. Contests such as Miss War Worker and Miss Civil Service often functioned as stepping stones to larger competitions. At all levels, pageants exemplified codes of femininity, class, sexuality, and race that shaped the narratives of the settler nation. A union-organized pageant such as Queen of the Dressmakers, for example, might uplift working-class women, but immigrant women need not apply. Queen of the Maple Leaf demonstrates how these contests connected female bodies to respectable, wholesome, middle-class femininity, locating their longevity squarely within their capacity to reassert the white heteropatriarchy at the heart of settler societies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aBeauty contestsxSocial aspectszCanada. 0aBeauty contestszCanadaxHistory. 0aFeminine beauty (Aesthetics)xSocial aspectszCanada. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Women's Studies.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311127253508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2020z978311127473708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of British Columbia Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311141765340uhttps://doi.org/10.59962/978077486414540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780774864145423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780774864145/original  a978-3-11-127253-5  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2020b2020  a978-3-11-127473-7  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2020b2020  a978-3-11-141765-3  University of British Columbia Complete eBook-Package 2020b2020  aGBV-deGruyter-alles